article.description:
Stephon Marbury scored 41 points, including 35 in the second half, to help the Phoenix Suns snap a four-game
losing streak with a 118-112 win over the Milwaukee Bucks on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Marbury scores 35 in second half alone
article.linkText: Marbury's 41 drives visiting Suns over Bucks
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Stephon Marbury knew somebody had to take charge if the Phoenix Suns were going to snap their four-game losing streak Wednesday night, so he did it himself.
Marbury

Marbury scored 35 points in the second half and finished with 41 as the Suns beat the Milwaukee Bucks, 118-112. Marbury surpassed 40 for the fourth time this season and the second time this month, finishing two points shy of his season high. "Tonight I felt the only way we were going to win was if we played hard defense, attacked them all night and rebounded the ball,'' Marbury said. "We got them in a running game and got the edge.'' Phoenix coach Frank Johnson said, "Steph wouldn't allow us to lose. He made stops and some defensive plays. He was pretty much all over the place. He knows where to look for his offense.'' Joe Johnson added 20 points for Phoenix. Gary Payton led Milwaukee with 26 points. Sam Cassell had 24 points, and Toni Kukoc 23. Marbury scored 18 points in the third quarter to give Phoenix a nine-point lead going into the fourth quarter. The Bucks wiped out that margin in the first six minutes, and Tim Thomas sank a 3-pointer to put Milwaukee up 97-96 with 6:14 left. Marbury made two jumpers, and Dan Langhi added a third to give Phoenix a 105-100 lead with 3:47 left. The Bucks closed within a point, but another jumper by Langhi and Marbury's layup with 1:51 left put the Suns back up by five, 109-104. The Bucks never got closer. Marbury made three straight 3-pointers to help the Suns open up a double-digit lead in the third quarter. Phoenix built the margin to 13 at one point. "When he makes 3s, I don't know how you cover him,'' Bucks coach George Karl said. "You can run out and try to double him and give someone else a 3. We did better in the fourth quarter, but the last two games we just got beat by two great players.'' Milwaukee has given up 235 points in consecutive losses to Minnesota and Phoenix. Phoenix shot 51 percent in the first half and Johnson went 3-for-5 from 3-point range to lead the Suns with 15 points. Desmond Mason came off the bench in the second quarter and shot 4-for-6 to help the Bucks pull within six, 57-51, by halftime.

Game notes
The Suns have defeated the Bucks eight straight times. ... Both teams wore retro uniforms from 1968-69. ...The Bucks have played seven straight games against Western Conference foes. ... Bucks coach George Karl's Friends of Hoop Foundation will be part of a large renovation project for the former Pabst Brewery in Milwaukee. Karl plans to build a youth basketball and education facility as part of the business and housing development announced Wednesday.
